            <annotations>
                <annotation bg_color="ff3399ff" halign="0" height="70" show_boder="1" width="641" x="205" y="13">
                    <markup color="ffffffff" font_face="Arial" size="18"/><![CDATA[4 cylinder SI engine demonstrating the port fuel puddling model, in-cylinder wall temperature solver and flow models, and predictive SI combustion and knock model]]></annotation>
                <annotation bg_color="ff3399ff" height="569" show_boder="1" width="284" x="381" y="101">
                    <markup color="ffffffff" font_face="Dialog" size="12"/><![CDATA[Wall temperature calculated in conjunction with EngCylTWallSoln.  See "Modeling Cylinder Ports" in the Engine Performance User's Manual for a full discussion.

Port Injection fuel transport and film model is used in the FlowSplitPort and PipePort parts.]]></annotation>
                <annotation height="55" show_boder="1" width="451" x="279" y="766">
                    <markup color="ff333333" font_face="Dialog" size="12"/><![CDATA[For more details, see the "Model_Description" tab or double-click the icon below.]]></annotation>
            </annotations>
        </main>
        <subassembly id="s2" level="2" name="Model_Description" pa_id="0" size_x="1000" size_y="1000">
            <part_table/>
            <port_link_table/>
            <annotations>
                <annotation height="447" show_boder="1" width="792" x="29" y="24">
                    <markup font_face="Arial" size="18"/><![CDATA[The example 'SI_4cyl_SITurb_PortFuelFilm_TWallSoln' demonstrates the use of 'PipePort' components to model fuel puddling and evaporation in the intake ports.  It also demonstrates the use of the predictive SI combustion model and the in-cylinder wall temperature solver.  This model has the following unique features:

Port Fuel Model: The intake ports are modeled with 'PipePort' parts.  The 'InjAFSeqConn' part contains attributes defining properties of the fuel and the injection event.  When a 'PipePort' part is used, the fuel impingement onto the wall and the subsequent transport and evaporation of the fuel film is modeled.  The port walls are thermally linked to the cylinder.

In Cylinder Wall Temperature Solver: The 'EngCylTWallSoln' object is used in the EngCylinder.  The solver will use the data entered in this object to solve for the wall temperatures in the various zones of the cylinder component walls.

Predictive SI Combustion Model:  A 'EngCylCombSITurb' object is referenced in the cylinder, which predicts the burn rate by modeling the in-cylinder flame propagation.  The 'SITurb' object in turn references the 'EngCylFlame' object.  In addition, the 'EngCylFlow' reference object has been used in the cylinder. Tumble coefficients are used in the intake valves to accurately predict the turbulent kinetic energy.

A Knock model 'kinetic-fit' is used in the model to predict knock.]]></annotation>
            </annotations>
        </subassembly>
    </assembly_table>
